3 Consumption Concavity and Prudence
This section provides a set of tools necessary to prove our main results. We first define
what we mean by consumption concavity. Next, we define an operation we call a
‘counterclockwise concavification,’ which describes how either a liquidity constraint or
a risk affects the consumption function. The advantage of defining a counterclockwise
concavification in such general terms is that we can show that it heightens prudence of
the value function irrespective of the source of concavification. Since the relationship
between prudence and precautionary saving has already been established in the literature (Kimball, 1990), the tools in this section allows us to later establish how liquidity
constraints affect precautionary saving, via consumption concavity and prudence.

