This section first defines what we mean by consumption concavity. Next, we show that
consumption concavity is a property that recursively propagates, meaning that once
established in some period, it also holds in all prior periods under fairly general conditions.
Lastly, we define what we mean by greater consumption concavity, which allows us to
compare consumption functions.
We start by defining what we man when we say that the value function has property
local consumption concavity (CC).
Definition 1. (Local Consumption Concavity.)
In relation to a utility function u(c) with non-negative (u000 ≥ 0) and non-increasing
prudence, a function V (w) has property CC (alternately, strict CC) over the interval
between w1 and w2 , where w2 > w1 , if
V 0 (w) = u0 (c(w))
for some increasing function c(w) that satisfies concavity (alternately, strict concavity)
over the interval from w1 to w2 .
Since (even with constraints) V 0 (w) = u0 (c(w)) holds by the envelope theorem, V (w)
having property CC (alternately, strict CC) is the same as having a concave (alternately,
strictly concave) consumption function c(w).9 Note that the definition is restricted to
