5 Liquidity Constraints and Precautionary Saving
Section 4 established the relationship between liquidity constraints, consumption concavity, and prudence. This section takes the last step and derives the relationship between
liquidity constraints and precautionary saving. First, we explain the relationship between
the precautionary premium and absolute prudence. Next, we show how the introduction
of an additional constraint induces agents to increase precautionary saving when they
face a current risk in Theorem 2. Unfortunately, the results in Theorem 2 cannot
be generalized to an added risk or liquidity constraint in a later time period because
it may hide or transform the effects of current constraints or risks, and thereby affect
local precautionary saving. However, we still derive our most general results on liquidity
constraints and precautionary saving in Theorem 3: the introduction of a risk has a greater
precautionary effect in the presence of all future risks and constraints than in the absence
of any future risks or constraints. Or in other words (Corollary 2), the consumption
function is strictly concave in the presence of all future risks and constraints.

